  "text": "# Grafana Dashboard JSON Schema Version Migration Pipeline\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Grafana dashboard schema version migration pipeline consists of two parallel implementations: a backend migration system written in Go and a frontend migration system in TypeScript that mirrors the backend logic.\n\n## Backend Migration Pipeline (Go)\n\n### Migration Runner\nThe main migration runner is implemented in `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/migrate.go`. Key functions include:\n\n- **Initialize(dsInfoProvider)**: Initializes the migrator singleton with required dependencies and builds the version-to-function map from GetMigrations()\n- **Migrate(ctx, dash, targetVersion)**: The primary entry point that orchestrates the migration process. It:\n  1. Cleans up properties not included in the frontend save model\n  2. Applies frontend defaults to match DashboardModel constructor behavior\n  3. Runs the versioned migration pipeline sequentially\n  4. Adds built-in annotation query after all migrations\n  5. Cleans up the dashboard to match frontend getSaveModel behavior\n\n### Migration Registry\nThe versioned migration function registry is defined in `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migrations.go`:\n\n- **GetMigrations(dsInfoProvider)**: Returns a map[int]SchemaVersionMigrationFunc mapping version numbers (2-42) to their corresponding migration functions\n- **SchemaVersionMigrationFunc**: Type definition for migration functions with signature: `func(context.Context, map[string]interface{}) error`\n- **GetSchemaVersion(dash)**: Utility function to extract and parse the schema version from a dashboard object\n\n### Schema Versions and Current Limit\n- MIN_VERSION: 0\n- LATEST_VERSION: 42 (marked as FINAL version for v1 dashboard API)\n- Note: Schema version 42 is the final version. Per comments in DashboardMigrator.ts, no new migrations should be added; instead, panel-specific migrations should be implemented in individual panel plugin migration handlers.\n\n### Individual Migration Steps\nEach schema version from v2 to v42 has a corresponding migration function:\n\n**Early versions (v2-v15)**: Core dashboard structure and property migrations\n- v2: Services filter migration (legacy time/templating)\n- v3: Panel ID assignment\n- v4-v7: Graph panel migrations and structural changes\n- v8: InfluxDB query schema updates\n- v10: Table threshold migration\n- v12-v15: Template variable migrations\n\n**Grid layout era (v16-v17)**: Major structural transitions\n- v16: Upgrade to grid layout (from row-based layout)\n- v17: minSpan to maxPerRow conversion\n\n**Options standardization (v18-v32)**: Panel options and variable normalization\n- v18: Gauge options migration\n- v19-v21: Data link updates and variable syntax\n- v22-v27: Table migrations and repeated panel cleanup\n- v28-v32: Tag removal and query variable optimization\n\n**Datasource reference modernization (v33-v36)**: Evolution to UID-based datasource identification\n- v33: Datasource name to reference conversion (returns wrapped function requiring DataSourceInfoProvider)\n- v34: CloudWatch query migrations\n- v35: X-axis visibility preservation\n- v36: Datasource reference migration for annotations, variables, and panels (returns wrapped function requiring DataSourceInfoProvider)\n\n**Final refinements (v37-v42)**: Polish and feature additions\n- v37: Legend display mode normalization\n- v38: Table cell display mode migration\n- v39: TimeSeriesTable transformer options restructuring\n- v40: Refresh property type standardization\n- v41: Legacy time_options removal\n- v42: hideFrom functionality migration for visibility toggles\n\n### Frontend Defaults Application\nThe `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/frontend_defaults.go` applies DashboardModel constructor defaults before running migrations to match frontend behavior:\n- Sets default title, tags, timezone\n- Initializes time range, templating, annotations\n- Applies grid layout defaults\n- Ensures panel defaults for both top-level and nested (in-row) panels\n\n## Frontend Migration System (TypeScript)\n\n### DashboardMigrator Class\nImplemented in `public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardMigrator.ts`:\n\n- **DASHBOARD_SCHEMA_VERSION**: Constant set to 42 (final version)\n- **DashboardMigrator class**: Main migration orchestrator\n  - **updateSchema(old, targetSchemaVersion?)**: Implements version-specific migration logic for all 42 schema versions\n  - Mirrors backend logic with TypeScript-specific implementations (e.g., InfluxDB field migrations, table cell options, data links)\n  - Uses panel upgrade handlers to systematically apply transformations across all panels\n\n### Integration Points\nThe frontend migration is invoked through:\n- **DashboardModel** (`public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardModel.ts`): Creates a DashboardMigrator instance in its `updateSchema()` private method (line 1127-1129)\n- **DashboardMigrator.ts updateSchema()**: Contains conditional blocks for each version (v2-v42) implementing:\n  - Property migrations (e.g., time, templating, annotations)\n  - Panel upgrades with transformation handlers\n  - Variable migrations\n  - Datasource reference updates\n  - Special handler functions for complex transformations\n\n### Helper Functions and Utilities\nThe DashboardMigrator includes utility functions for specific migration scenarios:\n- **migrateDatasourceNameToRef()**: Converts datasource names to structured references\n- **upgradeValueMappings()**: Migrates legacy value mapping formats\n- **ensureXAxisVisibility()**: Preserves axis visibility configurations\n- **upgradeToGridLayout()**: Converts row-based layouts to grid layout (v16)\n- **migrateCloudWatchQueries()**: Handles CloudWatch-specific transformations\n- **migrateTooltipOptions()**: Standardizes tooltip configurations\n\n## Testing Infrastructure\n\nComprehensive test files validate migration behavior:\n\n### Backend Tests\n- `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/migrate_test.go`: Tests the Migrate function and migration pipeline\n- Individual `v*_test.go` files: Unit tests for each schema version migration\n\n### Frontend Tests  \n- `public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardMigrator.test.ts`: Comprehensive migration test suite\n- `public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardMigratorToBackend.test.ts`: Compares backend and frontend migration results\n- `public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardMigratorSingleVersion.test.ts`: Tests single-version migrations\n\n## Migration Execution Flow\n\nWhen a dashboard is loaded:\n\n1. **Backend Path**: Dashboard is migrated via the Go migration pipeline to version 42\n2. **Frontend Path**: DashboardModel constructor instantiates DashboardMigrator and runs updateSchema() if the schema version is below the target\n3. **Consistency**: Both paths apply defaults and perform equivalent transformations to ensure identical results\n4. **Final State**: Dashboard is normalized to schema version 42 with all frontend constructor defaults applied\n\n## Key Design Patterns\n\n- **Version-based conditional logic**: Both backends use if-blocks checking version boundaries (oldVersion < X && targetVersion >= X)\n- **Sequential execution**: Migrations run sequentially from current version to target version\n- **Provider pattern**: V33 and V36 use a DataSourceInfoProvider to access runtime datasource information\n- **Panel upgrade handlers**: Frontend uses upgrade handler functions applied to all panels\n- **Schema finalization**: Version 42 is explicitly marked as final; future panel-specific features use plugin-level migrations\n\n## Important Notes\n\n- The migration pipeline handles complex scenarios: merged datasources, expression queries, nested panels in rows, repeated panels\n- Both backend and frontend implementations must remain in sync to ensure consistent dashboard behavior across environments\n- The schema version is independently tracked; frontend defaults are applied regardless of backend processing\n- Legacy panel types (like Angular plugins) are auto-migrated through separate plugin migration handlers"
}

